items.title: Former Liberal senator Cory Bernardi joins One Nation
items.standfirst: P auline Hanson will today announce the conservative figure as the latest recruit for her populist party.
items.content: Former Liberal senator Cory Bernardi has become the latest politician to join One Nation as the party surges ahead in polling.Pauline Hanson is expected to announce Bernardi would stand as the party's top upper house candidate in next month's South Australian election.Bernardi served as a senator for almost a decade until 2020.READ MORE: Can One Nation really upset the major parties? Why a 'reputation' test is looming for Pauline HansonHe later quit the Liberals and formed his own party, Australian Conservatives, but it failed to make an impact with voters.Following his departure from politics, Bernardi has been an oyster businessman and restaurateur on the Eyre Peninsula in SA.He aims to make those experiences in the regions and running a business part of his campaign focus.Ahead of today's announcement, Bernardi praised One Nation's progress in the polls on social media and said he would be "lending my shoulder to the ON wheel". "I'm so happy that their time has come, and the country looks intent on changing the current course of politics," he said. clusters.neutral_headline: Trump Threatens To Sue Comedian Trevor Noah

items.title: Trump threatens to sue Grammys host Trevor Noah over Epstein joke
items.standfirst: Donald Trump has threatened to sue comedian Trevor Noah over his joke during the Grammy Awards suggesting the US president had been to Jeffrey Epstein’s island.
items.content: Donald Trump has threatened to sue comedian Trevor Noah over his joke during the Grammy Awards suggesting the US president had been to Jeffrey Epstein’s island.

items.title: Trump threatens to sue comedian over Epstein joke at Grammys
items.standfirst: T he US president raged on social media over a quip the comedian made at yesterday's awards show.
items.content: US President Donald Trump overnight slammed the Grammy Awards and threatened to sue host Trevor Noah after the comedian joked about the president and Jeffrey Epstein's island."The Grammy Awards are the WORST, virtually unwatchable! Noah said, INCORRECTLY about me, that Donald Trump and Bill Clinton spent time on Epstein Island," Trump wrote on Truth Social.The president added he couldn't speak for Clinton, but that he has "never been to Epstein Island".READ MORE: Son of Norway's crown princess arrested before rape trial Trump, calling Noah a "total loser", said that "it looks like I'll be sending my lawyers" to sue him for "plenty" of money.The comedian made the quip in reference to the song of the year award, saying: "That is a Grammy that every artist wants almost as much as Trump wants Greenland, which makes sense … because Epstein's island is gone, he needs a new one to hang out with Bill Clinton."CNN has reached out to Noah for comment.READ MORE: 'Anti-China': Beijing hits out at Grammys for historic award The comments come after the Justice Department on Friday released more than three million pages of files related to Epstein, the convicted sex offender, including some that contain references to Trump, Clinton and other powerful figures.Trump and Clinton have denied any wrongdoing related to Epstein, who owned a private island in the Caribbean. Trump said last year that he rejected an invitation from Epstein to visit his island, in what he called a moment of good judgment."I never had the privilege of going to his island, and I did turn it down. A lot of people in Palm Beach were invited to his island. In one of my very good moments, I turned it down," Trump told reporters in July.READ MORE: Australian snowboarder killed in chairlift accident Clinton has also denied ever having visited Epstein's island.Trump frequently criticises Hollywood awards shows for making jabs at his expense.In his post overnight, he said Noah was "almost as bad as Jimmy Kimmel at the Low Ratings Academy Awards." Kimmel, who has frequently drawn the president's ire, called out Trump onstage in 2024 after he insulted the comedian on social media.The Grammys ceremony, which aired Sunday night on CBS, included numerous musicians criticising the Trump administration's federal immigration crackdown. Puerto Rican rapper Bad Bunny, who took home three awards, began one of his speeches by saying, "Before I say thanks to God, I'm gonna say: ICE out!"During another acceptance speech, delivered mostly in Spanish, Bad Bunny dedicated his album of the year win to "all the people who had to leave their homeland, their country to follow their dreams."Some celebrities wore pins that read "ICE out," which has been used at protests as a call to end operations by Immigration and Customs Enforcement.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

items.content: Tim knows firsthand the struggles of being homeless and navigating the weather, but it's experiences like his which will be the focus of a newly formed Australian Climate and Homelessness Alliance.
